default. We also advocate transparency in selection/promotion procedures - and in negotiating pay. Comments from a female Professor support this: “I think the system is 
defaultvery unfair - you can have tw
defaulto equally productive professors, with 
defaultProfessor A could be being paid nearly twice Professor B. Furthermore, because this is all negotiated secretly, Professor B may know nothing about this and think their salary is normal. Thi
defaults isn't hypothetical - I did a professorial pay-productivity review recently (for Athena SWAN) and while pay and productivity generally correlate, there are some notable disparities”. 
default2
default1
default. How the flow of money is managed within academia compared to 
defaultindustry is also something we would like to see examined. We have encountered frustration regarding inflexibility in
default the system
default, for example a female Fellow told us:
default “I can see that Universities are stymied by the limitations on how they can spend money an
defaultd hire people, and by the vast timescales it takes to find money to make new hires. In companies this seems to be easier to fix, because the funding is basically internal. 
default&#xa0;
defaultBut one of the reasons that Universities are so dreadful at all this is that they d
defaulton't feel they can do the logical things to solve the problem, because they don't have the money”. 
